{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2444"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2444"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.46,0.08,0.08,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108168"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2444"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90580"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1553"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5621"},{"type":"tags","id":"5773"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40360"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108168"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with an eight-hour history of severe left iliac fossa pain and fresh rectal bleeding. He has a medical history of venous thromboembolism diagnosed six months ago, for which he takes apixaban (last taken 12 hours ago). He takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is tender in the left iliac fossa. Digital rectal examination reveals fresh blood. His haemoglobin is 82 g/L (135-175). A CT scan reveals active contrast extravasation from a sigmoid diverticular vessel with a large amount of blood in the colon.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recombinant activated coagulation factor VII","Andexanet alfa","Idarucizumab","Vitamin K","Fresh frozen plasma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with life-threatening gastrointestinal bleeding while on apixaban, a direct factor Xa inhibitor. The priority is rapid reversal of anticoagulation to enable haemostasis. The timing of the last dose (12 hours ago) means there is still significant anticoagulant effect present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAndexanet alfa\u003C/strong\u003E is specifically designed to reverse factor Xa inhibitors, including apixaban. It acts as a decoy protein that binds and sequesters factor Xa inhibitors, rapidly reversing their anticoagulant effects. It is the most appropriate option when available. The effect is immediate but temporary, lasting approximately two hours after administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecombinant activated coagulation factor VII\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for reversing factor Xa inhibitors. It also carries a significant risk of thrombotic complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdarucizumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a specific reversal agent for dabigatran (a direct thrombin inhibitor) and would not be effective for reversing apixaban. It is important to know which anticoagulant the patient is taking to select the appropriate reversal agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E is only effective for reversing warfarin and does not affect direct oral anticoagulants like apixaban. It works by promoting the synthesis of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors, which is irrelevant to the mechanism of action of factor Xa inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFresh frozen plasma\u003C/strong\u003E is ineffective for reversing direct oral anticoagulants and would require large volumes that could cause fluid overload. It does not contain sufficient concentrations of clotting factors to overcome direct factor Xa inhibition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter achieving haemostasis, the decision to restart anticoagulation should balance bleeding and thrombotic risks. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Andexanet alfa is the specific reversal agent for factor Xa inhibitors including apixaban.","Urgent reversal of anticoagulation is required for life-threatening bleeding while on factor Xa inhibitors.","The timing of last dose is important in determining the need for reversal agents."],"references":["Andexxa. Therapeutic Goods Administration. Updated 12 July 2023. Available from: https://www.tga.gov.au/resources/auspmd/andexxa","Ward C, Conner G, Donnan G, Gallus A, McRae S. Practical management of patients on apixaban: a consensus guide. Thromb J; 2013: 11(27).","Therapeutic Guidelines. Anticoagulant therapy. Victoria: eTG; 2018 [edited Aug 2020; cited 2020 december 23]. Available from: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=anticoagulant-therapy\u0026guidelineName=Cardiovascular#toc_d1e831."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90580"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2444"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90580"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-07T18:12:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-07T18:13:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2444"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108168"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null